	The domain system is fundamentally flawed....

I think this is debatable.  Granted, inverse queries should be handled
better.  But a distributed naming system is inherently different from
a simple table look-up system because of the potential for soft errors.
What needs to be done is have the applications pass along some indication
(to the resolver? server?) of how hard they want to try to get the "right"
information.  In other words, you want degrees of name look-up, like
"give this a shot but if you don't hear anything in a few seconds give up",
to "I really need to know this answer; try real hard on this one". If you
can't get a name, often a numeric address is acceptable.

If you think the domain name server is bad, Sun's Yellow Pages has a worse
problem since there is no soft error code at all!

  -- WIN

